05800nam a22006615i 9781501727023DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017270237 a10.7591/97815017270232doi  a(DE-B1597)515196  a(OCoLC)1083581480  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0042402bisacsh04a1972221 aClowes, Edith W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFiction's Overcoat :bRussian Literary Culture and the Question of Philosophy /cEdith W. Clowes. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b10 halftones, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Transliteration and Translation -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. THE DISPLACEMENT OF PHILOSOPHY (1820s-1860s) -- t1. The Possibility of a Russian Philosophy: Language and Reader in a New Philosophical Culture (1820s-1830s) -- t2. Competing Discourses: Philosophy Marginalized -- t3. The Parting of the Ways: Chernyshevsky, Dostoevsky, and the Seeds of Russian Philosophical Discourse -- tPart Two. THE BIRTH OF RUSSIAN PHILOSOPHY (1870s-1920s) -- t4. Philosophical Language between Revelation and Reason: Solovyov's Search for Total Unity -- t5. Philosophy as Tragedy: Shestov and His Russian Audience -- t6. Philosophy in the Breach: Rozanov's Philosophical Roguery and the Destruction of Civil Discourse -- t7. Philosophy as Epic Drama: Berdiaev's Philosophy of the Creative Act -- tPart Three. THE SURVIVAL OF RUSSIAN PHILOSOPHICAL CULTURE ( 1920s-1950s) -- t8. Image and Concept: Losev's "Great Synthesis of Higher Knowledge" and the Tragedy of Philosophy -- t9. The Matter of Philosophy: Dialectical Materialism and Platonov's Quest after Questioning -- t10. "Sheer Philosophy" and "Vegetative Thinking": Pasternak's Suspension and Preservation of Philosophy -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: The Generations and Networks of Russian Philosophy -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIf Dostoevsky claimed that all Russian writers of his day "came out from Gogol's 'Overcoat,'" then Edith W. Clowes boldly expands his dramatic image to describe the emergence of Russian philosophy out from under the "overcoat" of Russian literature. In Fiction's Overcoat, Clowes responds to the view, commonly held by Western European and North American thinkers, that Russian culture has no philosophical tradition. If that is true, she asks, why do readers everywhere turn to the classics of Russian literature, at least in part because Russian writers so famously engage universal questions, because they are so "philosophical"? Her answer to this question is a lively and comprehensive volume that details the origins, submergence, and re-emergence of a rich and vital Russian philosophical tradition.During the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, Russian philosophy emerged in conversation with narrative fiction, radical journalism, and speculative theology, developing a distinct cultural discourse with its own claim to authority and truth. Leading Russian thinkers—Berdiaev, Losev, Rozanov, Shestov, and Solovyov—made philosophy the primary forum in which Russians debated metaphysical, aesthetic, and ethical questions as well as issues of individual and national identity. That debate was tragically truncated by the events of 1917 and the rise of the Soviet empire. Today, after seventy years of enforced silence, this particularly Russian philosophical culture has resurfaced. Fiction's Overcoat serves as a welcome guide to its complexities and nuances.Historians and cultural critics will find in Clowes's book the story of the increasing refinement and diversification of Russian cultural discourse, philosophers will find an alternative to the Western philosophical tradition, and students of literature will enjoy the opportunity to rethink the great Russian novelists—particularly Dostoevsky, Pasternak, and Platonov—as important voices in the process of shaping and sustaining a new philosophy and ensuring its survival into our own age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aHistory. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172702340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501727023423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501727023/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK